UNIT 4

Software Requirement Analysis and Specification

📌 Introduction to System and Software Requirements

  • The Software Requirement Specification (SRS) is a formal document that defines a software system’s functional and non-functional requirements.
  • It serves as a contract 📜 between stakeholders and developers, ensuring clarity and avoiding miscommunication.
  • Helps teams develop software that meets user needs, business goals, and technical constraints.

🔹 Scenario:
A hospital management system 🏥 requires an SRS document to define patient record storage, doctor schedules, and data security. Without it, miscommunication could lead to errors in software development.

⚡ Types of Software Requirements

1️⃣ Functional Requirements ⚙️ (What the system should do)

  • Define the core functionality of a system.
  • Specify data inputs, processing logic, and expected outputs.
  • Captured using use cases, flowcharts, and structured text.

📌 Key Functional Requirements:
✅ User Authentication – Logging in securely. 🔐
✅ Data Processing – Storing and retrieving data. 📊
✅ Business Logic Implementation – Ensuring system rules. ⚖️
✅ User Interface Behavior – Displaying data, alerts, etc. 🖥️

🔹 Example:
An e-commerce platform 🛒 must allow users to browse products, add to cart, and complete purchases via a secure checkout process.

2️⃣ Non-Functional Requirements 🛡️ (How the system should perform)

  • Define performance, security, reliability, and usability constraints.
  • Ensure efficiency, maintainability, and fault tolerance.

📌 Key Non-Functional Requirements:
✅ Security – Data encryption and user authentication 🔐
✅ Performance – Fast response times under load ⚡
✅ Interoperability – Compatibility with other systems 🔄
✅ Disaster Recovery – Backup and recovery solutions 🛠️

🔹 Example:
A banking system 🏦 must process transactions within 5 seconds and prevent unauthorized access through multi-factor authentication.

📜 Software Requirement Specification (SRS)

The SRS document serves as a blueprint 📑 for software development.

📍 Purpose of SRS:

✔️ Ensures all requirements are well-defined.
✔️ Helps developers understand stakeholder needs.
✔️ Serves as a reference for testing & validation.

📌 Key Elements of SRS:

1️⃣ Functional & Non-Functional Requirements
2️⃣ System Constraints & Limitations
3️⃣ Performance & Usability Metrics
4️⃣ External System Interactions

🔹 Scenario:
An airline reservation system ✈️ requires an SRS document defining seat selection, ticket booking, and refund policies. A well-defined SRS helps avoid conflicts between developers and stakeholders.

🔍 Characteristics of a Good SRS Document

✔️ Correctness – Must accurately reflect user requirements.
✔️ Completeness – Covers all aspects, leaving no ambiguity.
✔️ Consistency – No conflicting requirements.
✔️ Unambiguousness – Every requirement has a clear, single interpretation.
✔️ Modifiability – Easily adaptable to changes.
✔️ Testability – Enables validation through testing.
✔️ Traceability – Links requirements to design and code.

🔹 Scenario:
A ride-sharing app 🚗 needs an SRS that includes driver tracking, fare calculation, and safety features. If ambiguities exist, developers may misunderstand user needs.

📌 Requirement Engineering Process

Requirement Engineering involves gathering, analyzing, and documenting software requirements systematically.

📍 Steps in Requirement Engineering:

1️⃣ Feasibility Study – Checks if the project is viable.
2️⃣ Requirement Gathering – Identifies user needs via surveys, interviews, etc.
3️⃣ SRS Documentation – Defines all requirements in a structured document.
4️⃣ Requirement Validation – Ensures clarity, feasibility, and completeness.

🔹 Scenario:
A company developing an AI chatbot 🤖 first analyzes feasibility, then gathers customer requirements, documents them, and finally validates if AI responses meet user expectations.

📌 Requirement Elicitation Process

Requirement elicitation ensures that developers understand what users truly need. It consists of:

1️⃣ Gathering Requirements – Identifying user needs.
2️⃣ Organizing Requirements – Prioritizing based on importance.
3️⃣ Negotiation & Discussion – Resolving conflicts between stakeholders.
4️⃣ Documentation – Creating a formal requirement specification.

🔹 Scenario:
A hotel booking platform 🏨 conducts interviews and surveys to collect user expectations and prioritize key features like online payment, room selection, and cancellation policies.

📌 Requirement Elicitation Techniques

1️⃣ Interviews 🎤

  • One-on-one or group discussions with users.
  • Can be structured (predefined questions) or open-ended.

🔹 Scenario:
A university 🎓 interviews students and faculty to design a course registration system 📚.

2️⃣ Surveys & Questionnaires 📋

  • Collect large-scale feedback through structured forms.
  • Helps in prioritizing system features.

🔹 Scenario:
A mobile banking app 📱 conducts a survey to determine which features users value the most, like bill payments or loan applications.

3️⃣ Task & Domain Analysis 🔍

  • Studying existing systems to identify improvements.
  • Uses industry best practices for reference.

🔹 Scenario:
A warehouse automation system 🏭 analyzes current logistics to optimize product tracking and storage management.

4️⃣ Brainstorming 💡

  • A team discussion to generate innovative ideas.
  • Encourages creative problem-solving.

🔹 Scenario:
A gaming company 🎮 holds a brainstorming session to introduce new multiplayer features in their upcoming game.

5️⃣ Prototyping 🏗️

  • Builds an early model of the software for feedback.
  • Helps in refining user requirements before final development.

🔹 Scenario:
A food delivery app 🍔 develops a prototype to test navigation, order tracking, and restaurant listings before full-scale development.

6️⃣ Observation 👀

  • Directly observing user interactions with existing systems.
  • Identifies pain points and improvement areas.

🔹 Scenario:
An airport management system ✈️ observes passenger check-in and baggage handling to streamline operations.

🎯 Conclusion

📌 Requirement analysis ensures software meets user needs efficiently.
📌 SRS serves as a contract between developers and stakeholders.
📌 A structured elicitation process prevents misunderstandings and costly revisions.

By following a systematic approach, software engineers develop high-quality, efficient, and user-friendly systems! 🚀
